I get that lobster rolls are gonna be quite pricey, averaging in price from quality to quantity. There's a decent balance to these here and I would have given a 3-4 star review and I'll explain why. I went simple, classic lobster roll combo that includes a side and a drink. Came out around $23. My choice of side was easy, French fries! right!? Wrong. The order of fries came out 10 minutes after they had brought out my entree, and when I received the fries, half were burnt the other half stuck together. For the price I would have imagined hand cut fries or at least decently cooked to near perfection. But no, they're what you'd expect from Oven baked fries at home and you forget to take them out. Then we come to the drink. There's no fountain drinks there, they have a small selection of Maine soda's. Yet again, for the price I would like to have a bigger selection of beverages and also take a refill if I choose. Would I recommend this place? It's a maybe. Would I recommend somewhere else vs here? Oh yeah. Easily and without remorse.

We ordered multiple items, here is our opinion, on a scale of 10:  Overall value: 2/10: we had two large entrees, two beers, fries and a small soup, total was $70. I appreciate cheap seafood isn’t good and good seafood isn’t cheap, but this felt like a spendy meal for a walk up.  Lobster roll, jumbo 7/10: lobster was fresh and tasty, bun could have been toasted more - really wanted to love this but didn’t hit the spot  Crab roll, jumbo 8/10: generous portion of crab meat, overflowing from bun, which could have been toasted just a bit longer  Lobster bisque 12/10: please just sell this by the gallon and let me enjoy it for three meals a day. Long time Luke's fan, and have visited them across multiple locations - my favorite being Market Street Philly. First time visiting the Georgetown location and I'm not impressed. The food was fine, although the size of the rolls in the Trio have shrunk pretty perceivably. Taste was fine, pricing was the usual. What I greatly disliked was the atmosphere. This joint is a safety and health hazard. It was hot, with no ventilation (leave alone air-conditioning), and an acrid smell of what must be smoke from the deep fat fryers. I wonder how the staff spend their day in that gas chamber, but there's no excuse for inflicting that on paying customers. If I'm counter tipping, the least I expect is a clean table (not with bits of seafood from previous diners), and some oxygen to breathe. I couldn't finish my food soon enough and get out. The lady clearing out the baskets proceeded to drop half a dozen of them all over the floor. Sloppy. The atmosphere in other Luke's outlets has always been cool, clean and fresh. That's what I want when I'm eating chilled seafood, not a place that smells of fryer oil and smoke. Won't return or recommend.

Avoid At All Costs  You may read online that this is a lovely little seafood shack that will make your night a success. Let me be very clear: these reviews are horrible, horrible lies.  It is overpriced, mediocre seafood in diminutive portions, set in an unsanitary cramped shack with music ranging from Britney Spears to Jesse McCartney in the background. All the while pretending to be a charming Maine lobster shack. Luke's Lobster is a filthy pack of lies.  And if you ignore this and go anyway? Don't get the Noah's Ark. At least follow that advice.

Lobster rolls done right, without the mayo-based sauce. I love lobster, and I've been to one or two NYC locations as well. Always seems very fresh. I don't tend to like lobster dishes and prefer just eating them steamed and destroying them but this is the next best thing.  Will say that I didn't think much of the non-lobster offerings.... Shrimp was just average and I don't remember loving much else. But the deliciousness of the lobster is enough for 5 stars from me. :)

Definitely long overdo review. I now live in Chicago but definitely on my list of spots to return to when I visit DC in the near future.  My first, of several subsequent visits, was shortly after they opened, I came here for lunch with my friend after walking around/shopping in Georgetown much of the day.  It absolutely lives up to much of the hype. Great lobster rolls! Great crab rolls! The lobster grilled cheese is amazing! Everything is fresh and perfectly cooked. It does seem a bit pricey for what you get but worth the splurge. :-D  The space itself is on the small side, any small group would immediately dominate the space. While Luke's seems pretty popular, at least in my circle of friends, I have never waited in line here. It's almost always empty, I would guess it has to be the fact that it is slightly "hidden," not directly on M street and towards the tail end of all the shops.

What a great find!  My wife, daughter and I were looking for a good dinner spot... seafood that wouldn't break the bank... saw some reviews on this place and decided to give it a try.  AWESOME food and the staff was really friendly.  The restaurant itself is small but nice.
